14. Difference between Scanner and BufferedReader?
-->The primary difference between Scanner and BufferedReader in Java lies in their performance and parsing capabilities. 
    While Scanner is more convenient for parsing primitive types, BufferedReader is significantly faster for reading 
    large amounts of text.
| Feature           | Scanner                                        | BufferedReader                                          |
| ----------------- | ---------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Package**       | `java.util`                                    | `java.io`                                               |
| **Parsing**       | Built-in parsing (`nextInt()`, `nextDouble()`) | Reads only text → manual parsing (`Integer.parseInt()`) |
| **Speed**         | Slower (uses regex + parsing overhead)         | Faster (uses buffering)                                 |
| **Buffer Size**   | Small (~1 KB)                                  | Large (~8 KB)                                           |
| **Thread Safety** | Not thread-safe (not synchronized)             | Thread-safe (synchronized)                              |
| **Exceptions**    | Hides `IOException`                            | Explicitly throws `IOException`                         |
| **Ease of Use**   | Very easy for beginners                        | Slightly complex                                        |
| **Best Use Case** | User input, small programs                     | Large input, competitive coding                         |



15. Why does Scanner skip input after reading numbers?
-->In Java, a Scanner appears to "skip" input when you call nextLine() immediately after a numeric method like nextInt() or nextDouble(). 
    Why it Happens
    The issue is caused by how different Scanner methods handle the input buffer: 
    
nextInt() and others: These methods read only the specific data type (the number) and stop. They leave the newline character (\n)—created
    when you press the "Enter" key—sitting in the buffer.
    
nextLine(): This method is designed to read everything until it finds a line separator. Since the \n from your previous numeric
    input is the very next thing in the buffer, nextLine() consumes it immediately and returns an empty string. To the user, it 
    looks like the program skipped the prompt entirely. 


